      1. Climate


        The climate in the villages of the number one block of dentistry is characterized by a hot or summer. The months of May to June are usually 34 degrees to 45 degrees Celsius. The monsoon is generally dry except for the south-west monsoon but heavy rainfall is observed from July to September. The amount of rain is so much that the farmland is destroyed by the bullets and the houses fall.

        The southwest monsoon season lasts from October to December, resulting in occasional rainfall. From then on the northeast monsoon begins to come and January to March is called the winter season. Extreme heat in the summer and heavy rains in the rainy season destroy everything from agricultural land to houses. Winter temperatures range from 8 C to 12 C.

    5. Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI)


      Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) Vegetation by measuring the difference between near-infrared (which vegetation strongly reflects) and red light (which vegetation

      absorbs). NDVI

      always ranges from -1 to +1. Healthy Vegetation (chlorophyll) reflects more near-infrared (NIR) and Green Light compared to other wavelength. But it absorb more then red

      and blue light. Normalized Difference

      Vegetation index (NDVI) use the NIR in its formula

      NDVI = (NIR – Red) (NIR + Red)

        1. Satellite Data

          • Landsat-8 OLI/TIRS Data


            The Landsat 8 payload consists of two science instrument sensors: the Operational land imager (OLI) and the Thermal Infrared Sensor (TIRS). OLI will collect band name, bandwidth (μm) and resolution (m). These two sensors converge of the global landmass at a spatial resolution 30 meters in visible, NIR, SWIR and 100 meters for thermal and 15 meters for panchromatic band. A standard false colour composite (FCC) was generated from bands 5, 4, 3( Near Infrared, Red, Green) coded in red, green, blue colour scheme through in ERDAS imagine. (https://glovis.usgs.gov/)
